  <Fragment slot="extra-sections">
    <section>
      <h2>How to use a scale for espresso (without overthinking it)</h2>
      <p>Here is the simple version: pick one recipe and make it boringly repeatable. Something like <strong>18 g in → 36 g out</strong>. Then keep that ratio steady while you adjust grind size. That is how you learn what changes actually do.</p>
      <p>When you pull a shot, put your cup on the scale, tare to zero, and watch the last few grams like a hawk. Espresso is polite at the start and chaotic at the end. If your scale feels a bit laggy, stop a touch early and let the flow carry you over the line.</p>
      <p>If you want more help dialing, our <a href="/posts/best-espresso-machine-under-200.html">best espresso machine under $200 guide</a> and <a href="/posts/burr-grinder-settings-for-espresso.html">espresso grind setting guide</a> are great next reads.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>How to use a scale for pour over (the “no guesswork” version)</h2>
      <p>For pour over, a scale turns “that looked about right” into repeatable coffee. Start with a simple ratio like <strong>1:16</strong> (20 g coffee → 320 g water). Keep that steady for a week. Once the ratio is stable, you can actually taste what grind size and pouring style are doing.</p>
      <p>Use the timer like a set of checkpoints. Start it on your first pour, hit your bloom weight, then hit your final weight, then notice the drawdown. When something tastes off, you have real clues instead of pure vibes.</p>
      <p>If you want a deeper ratio walkthrough, bookmark our <a href="/posts/coffee-brewing-ratio-guide.html">coffee brewing ratio guide</a>.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Common coffee scale mistakes</h2>
      <p><strong>Buying the biggest platform you can find.</strong> For espresso, big can be a problem. Measure your tray space first.</p>
      <p><strong>Ignoring button layout.</strong> If tare and timer are annoying, you will stop using them. That is not “user error.” That is bad design.</p>
      <p><strong>Letting steam live on the scale.</strong> Steam is basically a slow leak into electronics. Wipe it down. Keep it dry.</p>
      <p><strong>Changing five things at once.</strong> Keep dose and ratio steady, then change one thing. It is the fastest way to get better coffee without getting confused.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The espresso tray fit test (do this before you buy)</h2>
      <p>Here is a boring truth that saves you money: most coffee scale regrets are not about accuracy. They are about <em>fit</em>. A scale can be “great” and still make you miserable if it does not physically work with your machine and cup.</p>
      <p>Before you buy, do a quick check at your espresso setup:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Measure your drip tray space (width and depth).</li>
        <li>Put your most-used cup on the tray and look at what space is left.</li>
        <li>Think about clearance: will the scale + cup block the spouts, steam wand, or bottomless portafilter flow?</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If your current setup feels cramped, lean toward compact picks like the TIMEMORE Nano or the KitchenTour style mini. If your setup is roomy, you can prioritize readability and comfort instead of playing Tetris every morning.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What “fast response” feels like in real espresso</h2>
      <p>People talk about response speed like it is a spec. To me, it is a feeling. A fast scale feels like you and the numbers are moving together. A slow scale feels like you are watching espresso through a security camera feed from five seconds ago.</p>
      <p>If your scale is a little laggy, do not panic. Use this simple trick: pick a repeatable target (say 36 g out), then aim to stop the pump at 34–35 g and let the flow finish the last bit. After a few shots, you will learn your machine’s “coast” and your scale’s lag, and you will land on target more often.</p>
      <p>Also: do not chase perfection if your grinder is still inconsistent. A scale makes your decisions clearer, but the grinder still decides how the shot behaves. If you are still dialing in, our <a href="/posts/best-burr-grinder-for-espresso.html">best burr grinder for espresso guide</a> can help you tighten the whole system.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
