      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying guide: how to choose a scale that fits your routine</h2>

      <h3>1) Espresso-first? Buy for speed and footprint</h3>
      <p>If espresso is your daily driver, the “feel” of the readout matters. A fast display makes it easier to stop shots on time. And footprint is huge: if the scale barely fits, you will hate using it. Do not ignore this.</p>

      <h3>2) Pour-over-first? Buy for readability and timer comfort</h3>
      <p>For pour over, you want to see the numbers from kettle height and tap the timer without fumbling. If the display is tiny or the buttons feel awkward, your pours get messy and you lose the point of timing.</p>

      <h3>3) Look for 0.1 g precision (and do not pay extra for “lab vibes”)</h3>
      <p>0.1 g readings are the practical sweet spot for coffee. Anything less precise feels sloppy for espresso yields. Anything more precise rarely improves taste — it mostly improves your anxiety.</p>

      <h3>4) Decide if you want app features or phone-free calm</h3>
      <p>App features are great when you love data. If you do not, they can feel like chores. Be honest with yourself. The best gear is the gear you enjoy using.</p>

      <h3>5) Plan for water, steam, and mess (because coffee is messy)</h3>
      <p>Scales live in the splash zone. Espresso drips. Kettles steam. Pour-over brewers spill. If you want your scale to last, treat moisture like the enemy.</p>
      <p>Two easy habits help a lot: use a thin silicone mat if your scale supports it (it catches drips), and wipe the top after every brew session. Also, do not store your scale under the espresso machine where it gets constantly misted by steam. That is basically slow-motion water damage.</p>
      <p>Finally, think about auto-off. Some scales shut off faster than you want mid-brew, which is infuriating. If you are a slow, careful pour-over brewer, prioritize models with a workflow that does not fight you.</p>
    </BuyingGuideSection>
